To render a Pug template using Node.js, you'll need to use the `pug` package, which is the official package for compiling and rendering Pug templates. Here's an example of Node.js code that demonstrates how to render a Pug template:

1. First, make sure you have the `pug` package installed in your project. You can install it using npm or yarn:

```bash
npm install pug
# or
yarn add pug
```

2. Once the package is installed, you can use the following Node.js code to render a Pug template:

```javascript
const pug = require('pug');
const fs = require('fs');

// Read the Pug template file
const pugTemplate = fs.readFileSync('path/to/your/template.pug', 'utf8');

// Compile the Pug template
const compiledTemplate = pug.compile(pugTemplate);

// Data to pass to the template
const templateData = {
  title: 'My Page',
  content: 'Hello, world!',
};

// Render the compiled template with the data
const renderedHTML = compiledTemplate(templateData);

console.log(renderedHTML);
```

Make sure to replace `'path/to/your/template.pug'` with the actual path to your Pug template file. You can also modify the `templateData` object to include the data you want to pass to the template.

This code will compile and render the Pug template and then output the resulting HTML. You can use this HTML in your application as needed.

Remember that this is a basic example, and in a real-world application, you might want to handle errors, organize your code better, and possibly use frameworks like Express.js to simplify the rendering process.

