<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Blue Bar Example</title>
  <style>
    /* Styling for the blue bar */
    .blue-bar {
      background-color: blue;
      color: white;
      padding: 10px;
      display: flex;
      justify-content: space-between;
      align-items: center;
    }

    /* Styling for the dropdown menu */
    .dropdown {
      position: relative;
    }

    .dropdown-content {
      display: none;
      position: absolute;
      background-color: #f9f9f9;
      min-width: 160px;
      box-shadow: 0px 8px 16px 0px rgba(0,0,0,0.2);
      z-index: 1;
    }

    .dropdown:hover .dropdown-content {
      display: block;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <!-- Blue bar with dropdown menu and image -->
  <div class="blue-bar">
    <div>Logo</div>
    <div class="dropdown">
      <span>Dropdown</span>
      <div class="dropdown-content">
        <a href="#">Option 1</a>
        <a href="#">Option 2</a>
        <a href="#">Option 3</a>
      </div>
    </div>
    <img src="image.jpg" alt="Image">
  </div>
</body>
</html>
```

In this example, a blue bar is created using a `<div>` element with the class `blue-bar`. The bar contains three sections:

1. The first `<div>` contains the "Logo" (you can replace it with your actual logo or text).
2. The second `<div>` with the class `dropdown` represents the dropdown menu. When hovered over, the dropdown menu content appears. This is achieved using CSS to show and hide the `.dropdown-content`.
3. The `<img>` tag at the end adds an image. Make sure to replace `"image.jpg"` with the actual path to your image.

