Sure, here's an example of a simple timer implemented in JavaScript that updates an HTML element to display the elapsed time:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Timer Example</title>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Timer:</h1>
  <p id="timer">0 seconds</p>

  <script>
    // Get the HTML element to display the timer
    const timerElement = document.getElementById('timer');

    // Start time when the page loads
    let startTime = Date.now();

    // Update the timer element
    function updateTimer() {
      const currentTime = Date.now();
      const elapsedTime = Math.floor((currentTime - startTime) / 1000); // Convert to seconds
      timerElement.textContent = `${elapsedTime} seconds`;
    }

    // Update the timer every second
    setInterval(updateTimer, 1000);
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

In this example, the JavaScript code calculates the elapsed time in seconds since the page loaded and updates the content of the `<p>` element with the id `timer`. The `setInterval` function is used to call the `updateTimer` function every second, ensuring that the timer displayed on the page is continuously updated.

You can customize this code further by adding more features, improving the UI, or integrating it into a larger application.

